<paragraph pageId="10" pageNumber="117">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="118" pageId="10" pageNumber="117">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pic" baseAuthorityYear="1904" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Aegomorphus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aegomorphus obscurior" order="Coleoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="117" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obscurior">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="117">Aegomorphus obscurior</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was recently raised to the species level by 
<bibRefCitation author="Hilszczanski, J" journalOrPublisher="Genus" pageId="24" pageNumber="131" pagination="61 - 63" refId="B31" refString="Hilszczanski, J, 2008. The synonymy and distribution of Aegomorphus obscurior (Pic, 1904), new status and occurrence of A. francottei Sama, 1994 in Poland (Coleoptera: Cerambycidae). Genus 19 (1): 61 - 63" title="The synonymy and distribution of Aegomorphus obscurior (Pic, 1904), new status and occurrence of A. francottei Sama, 1994 in Poland (Coleoptera: Cerambycidae)." volume="19" year="2008">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Hilszczański">Hilszczanski</normalizedToken>
(2008)
</bibRefCitation>
. After the revision of specimens, it is known to be broadly distributed in Russia and in the Siberian part of Kazakhstan (
<bibRefCitation author="Danilevsky, M" journalOrPublisher="Eversmannia" pageId="23" pageNumber="130" pagination="8 - 10" refId="B14" refString="Danilevsky, M, Shapovalov, AM, 2007. The occurrence of Aegomorphus wojtylai Hilszczanski et Bystrowski, 2005 (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae) in Russia. Eversmannia 9: 8 - 10" title="The occurrence of Aegomorphus wojtylai Hilszczanski et Bystrowski, 2005 (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae) in Russia." volume="9" year="2007">Danilevsky and Shapovalov 2007</bibRefCitation>
) 
<pageBreakToken pageId="11" pageNumber="118" start="start">as</pageBreakToken>
well as in Mongolia (
<bibRefCitation author="Hilszczanski, J" journalOrPublisher="Genus" pageId="24" pageNumber="131" pagination="61 - 63" refId="B31" refString="Hilszczanski, J, 2008. The synonymy and distribution of Aegomorphus obscurior (Pic, 1904), new status and occurrence of A. francottei Sama, 1994 in Poland (Coleoptera: Cerambycidae). Genus 19 (1): 61 - 63" title="The synonymy and distribution of Aegomorphus obscurior (Pic, 1904), new status and occurrence of A. francottei Sama, 1994 in Poland (Coleoptera: Cerambycidae)." volume="19" year="2008">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Hilszczański">Hilszczanski</normalizedToken>
2008
</bibRefCitation>
). In Europe, it reaches Latvia (
<bibRefCitation author="Telnov, D" journalOrPublisher="Walter de Gruyter, Berlin / Boston" pageId="26" pageNumber="133" publicationUrl="http://leb.daba.lv/addenda.pdf" refId="B66" refString="Telnov, D, 2016. Species recorded for Latvia after the publication of the &quot;Check-list of Latvian beetles (Insecta: Coleoptera)&quot;. http://leb.daba.lv/addenda.pdf" title="Species recorded for Latvia after the publication of the &quot; Check-list of Latvian beetles (Insecta: Coleoptera) &quot;." url="http://leb.daba.lv/addenda.pdf" year="2016">Telnov 2016</bibRefCitation>
) and eastern Poland (
<bibRefCitation author="Hilszczanski, J" journalOrPublisher="Genus" pageId="24" pageNumber="131" pagination="61 - 63" refId="B31" refString="Hilszczanski, J, 2008. The synonymy and distribution of Aegomorphus obscurior (Pic, 1904), new status and occurrence of A. francottei Sama, 1994 in Poland (Coleoptera: Cerambycidae). Genus 19 (1): 61 - 63" title="The synonymy and distribution of Aegomorphus obscurior (Pic, 1904), new status and occurrence of A. francottei Sama, 1994 in Poland (Coleoptera: Cerambycidae)." volume="19" year="2008">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Hilszczański">Hilszczanski</normalizedToken>
2008
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Danilevsky, ML" journalOrPublisher="HSC, Moscow" pageId="23" pageNumber="130" publicationUrl="http://cerambycidae.net/catalog.pdf" refId="B11" refString="Danilevsky, ML, 2017a. Catalogue of Palaearctic Cerambycoidea. [Updated: 15.02.2017] http://cerambycidae.net/catalog.pdf" title="Catalogue of Palaearctic Cerambycoidea. [Updated: 15.02.2017]" url="http://cerambycidae.net/catalog.pdf" year="2017 a">Danilevsky 2017a</bibRefCitation>
). The species was recently included in the Mongolian fauna (
<bibRefCitation author="Hilszczanski, J" journalOrPublisher="Genus" pageId="24" pageNumber="131" pagination="61 - 63" refId="B31" refString="Hilszczanski, J, 2008. The synonymy and distribution of Aegomorphus obscurior (Pic, 1904), new status and occurrence of A. francottei Sama, 1994 in Poland (Coleoptera: Cerambycidae). Genus 19 (1): 61 - 63" title="The synonymy and distribution of Aegomorphus obscurior (Pic, 1904), new status and occurrence of A. francottei Sama, 1994 in Poland (Coleoptera: Cerambycidae)." volume="19" year="2008">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Hilszczański">Hilszczanski</normalizedToken>
2008
</bibRefCitation>
) based on four specimens that were collected 30 km north of Batsumber by B. Burakowski and H. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Szelęgiewicz">Szelegiewicz</normalizedToken>
in 1963. The larvae feed on dead trees or dead parts of living trees of their host plants: 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Fagaceae" genus="Quercus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Quercus robur" order="Fagales" pageId="11" pageNumber="118" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="robur">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="118">Quercus robur</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hilszczanski, J" journalOrPublisher="Genus" pageId="24" pageNumber="131" pagination="201 - 207" refId="B32" refString="Hilszczanski, J, Bystrowski, C, 2005. Aegomorphus wojtylai, a new species from Poland, with a key to European species of Aegomorphus Haldeman (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Genus 16 (2): 201 - 207" title="Aegomorphus wojtylai, a new species from Poland, with a key to European species of Aegomorphus Haldeman (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae)." volume="16" year="2005">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Hilszczański">Hilszczanski</normalizedToken>
and Bystrowski 2005
</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Betulaceae" genus="Betula" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Betula" order="Fagales" pageId="11" pageNumber="118" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="118">Betula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. and 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Betulaceae" genus="Alnus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Alnus" order="Fagales" pageId="11" pageNumber="118" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="118">Alnus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. (
<bibRefCitation author="Danilevsky, M" journalOrPublisher="Eversmannia" pageId="23" pageNumber="130" pagination="8 - 10" refId="B14" refString="Danilevsky, M, Shapovalov, AM, 2007. The occurrence of Aegomorphus wojtylai Hilszczanski et Bystrowski, 2005 (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae) in Russia. Eversmannia 9: 8 - 10" title="The occurrence of Aegomorphus wojtylai Hilszczanski et Bystrowski, 2005 (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae) in Russia." volume="9" year="2007">Danilevsky and Shapovalov 2007</bibRefCitation>
). The life cycle lasts two years. The adults are active from the second half of May (
<bibRefCitation author="Hilszczanski, J" journalOrPublisher="Genus" pageId="24" pageNumber="131" pagination="201 - 207" refId="B32" refString="Hilszczanski, J, Bystrowski, C, 2005. Aegomorphus wojtylai, a new species from Poland, with a key to European species of Aegomorphus Haldeman (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Genus 16 (2): 201 - 207" title="Aegomorphus wojtylai, a new species from Poland, with a key to European species of Aegomorphus Haldeman (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae)." volume="16" year="2005">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Hilszczański">Hilszczanski</normalizedToken>
and Bystrowski 2005
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="11" pageNumber="118">
A single male was reared from the top part of a broken trunk of the birch 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Betulaceae" genus="Betula" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Betula platyphylla" order="Fagales" pageId="11" pageNumber="118" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="platyphylla">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="118">Betula platyphylla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(approx. 10 cm in diameter) (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 7. Field photos of immature stages and habitats of typical Mongolian cerambycid species: A larches in forest steppe, the habitat of Lepturalia nigripes rufipennis B larva of L. nigripes in a birch stump C site in light taiga, the habitat of L. nigripes rufipennis and Agapanthia pilicornis pilicornis D site in forest steppe, the habitat of Clytus arietoides, Monochamus impluviatus impluviatus and M. sutor longulus E broken trunk of the birch in light taiga, the microhabitat of inter alia Xylotrechus hircus and Aegomorphus obscurior F birches in light taiga, the habitat of X. hircus, A. obscurior, Saperda scalaris hieroglyphica and Mesosa myops G larva of Xylotrechus pantherinus H larva of X. pantherinus deep in the wood of a standing willow trunk." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.739.23675.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/187660" pageId="11" pageNumber="118">7E</figureCitation>
) that was found in the light taiga habitat (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 7. Field photos of immature stages and habitats of typical Mongolian cerambycid species: A larches in forest steppe, the habitat of Lepturalia nigripes rufipennis B larva of L. nigripes in a birch stump C site in light taiga, the habitat of L. nigripes rufipennis and Agapanthia pilicornis pilicornis D site in forest steppe, the habitat of Clytus arietoides, Monochamus impluviatus impluviatus and M. sutor longulus E broken trunk of the birch in light taiga, the microhabitat of inter alia Xylotrechus hircus and Aegomorphus obscurior F birches in light taiga, the habitat of X. hircus, A. obscurior, Saperda scalaris hieroglyphica and Mesosa myops G larva of Xylotrechus pantherinus H larva of X. pantherinus deep in the wood of a standing willow trunk." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.739.23675.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/187660" pageId="11" pageNumber="118">7F</figureCitation>
). The same material was additionally inhabited by larvae of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Gebler" baseAuthorityYear="1825" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Xylotrechus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xylotrechus hircus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hircus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="118">Xylotrechus hircus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Saperda" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Saperda scalaris" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scalaris">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="118">Saperda scalaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Dalman" baseAuthorityYear="1817" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Mesosa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mesosa myops" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="118" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="myops">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="118">Mesosa myops</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Our findings constitute the second record of this species from Mongolia.
</paragraph>
